[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Introduction
[normal]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Th
[normal]e
[normal] Government is committed to promoting equality in the workplace as our 
[normal]track record 
[normal]on positive action, 
[normal]transparency, flexible working and
[normal] shared
[normal] parental leave demonstrate. 
[normal] 
[normal]We are committed to ensuring that the
[normal] 
[normal]Science, Technology, Engineering and Maths
[normal] 
[normal](STEM) 
[normal]workforce is diverse, reflect
[normal]s
[normal] wider society and makes use of all the talents available to it. 
[normal] 
[normal]D
[normal]espite positive progress, there are still too many groups under-represented in this sector. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Public Sector Equality D
[normal]uty
[normal] 
[normal]which came into force a
[normal]s part of the Equality Act 2010 
[normal]conveys on Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) as public 
[normal]authorities the duty to; 
[normal]advance equality of opportunity between people who share a protected characteristic and those who do not
[normal], foster good relations between people who share protected characteristics and those who do not
[normal] and eliminate
[normal] unlawful 
[normal]discrimi
[normal]nation
[normal], harassment and victimisation as defined by the Equality A
[normal]ct.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]When considering career progression for women in STEM it is important to consider the diversity of other careers as a comparator.  Although some STEM disciplines do particularly badly 
[normal]in the number of women they attract and retain, there remains a general problem with unequal 
[normal]career progression 
[normal]for women across the workforce as a whole.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Women are 46% of the workforce
[normal], but their representation falls in more senior positions: women ma
[normal]ke up only 33% of managers, directors and senior officials
[normal] and only 14
[normal]% of FTSE250 board members
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]Overall 
[normal]12 per cent 
[normal]of FTSE 100 board appointments since 1
[normal] 
[normal]March 201
[normal]3
[normal] have gone to women.
[normal]  
[normal]The proportions of women in management vary in different industr
[normal]ies. For example, women make up 55% of corporate managers and senior officials in the public sector but only 6% in retail, food, accommodation and services
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Women outnumber men in HE 
[normal]at undergraduate level
[normal]:
[normal] they have lower drop-out levels and better atta
[normal]inment levels. 
[normal] Although there is
[normal] variability in specific subject participation rates,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]women’s representation is higher than men’s in most subject areas.
[normal]  
[normal]Overall
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]48
[normal]% of students studying Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathem
[normal]atics (STEM) subjects 
[normal]are women:
[normal] this has remained fairly constant over the last decade.
[normal]  The vast majority of the
[normal]se women study Biological S
[normal]c
[normal]iences
[normal] and 
[normal]Subjects Allied to M
[normal]edicine
[normal] (which includes nursing). 
[normal] 
[normal]M
[normal]en still have 
[normal]much 
[normal]higher part
[normal]icipation in engineering and computer s
[normal]cience
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Figure 1[bold]:[bold] First Degree Entrants to UK HEIs (excluding the Open University) Gender Split by STEM subject area, academic year 2011/12
[normal]&#xa0;
