[normal]6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In 2011/12 47% of 
[normal]masters
[normal] students studying STEM subjects were female compared with 56% of masters students studying non-STEM subjects.  At PhD level, 44% of STEM PhD students were female compared with 51% in non-STEM subjects.  No central data is collected on lecturers specifical
[normal]ly
[normal], h
[normal]owever in 2011/12, of HEI staff whose academic function included teaching: 39% of those with a STEM cost-centre and 48% with a non-STEM cost-centre were female. In 2011/12, 21% of professors were female. 17% of professors with a STEM cost-centre were 
[normal]female and 26% of professors with a non-STEM cost-centre were female
[normal] (see 
[normal]A
[normal]ppendi
[normal]x A
[normal])
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal] As with the undergraduates, there will be differences 
[normal]in the level of female representation 
[normal]across disciplines within STEM.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government’s approach
[normal] to tackling lack of diversity in STEM careers
[normal] 
[normal]is to encourage diversity in the STEM workforce by 
[normal]raising awareness of different STEM careers and embedding and mainstreaming equality and diversity 
[normal]through a number of the programmes we fund, and those of th
[normal]e partners with which we work. This build
[normal]s
[normal] on the wider work of the government to promote inclusive workplaces. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A broad mix of STEM activities and wider societal programmes are supported by science and research 
[normal]funding
[normal] and these have a major impact on di
[normal]versity in the STEM workforce. 
[normal] 
[normal]These include the work of STEMNET
[normal] and the STEM Ambassadors to encourage a diverse STEM pipeline; the National Academies’ fellowships; Research Councils’ PhD and fellowships awards; and the Big Bang Fair
[normal] and 
[normal]National Scien
[normal]ce and Engineering Competition
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]Better value can be realised through these broader activities and through better direction of existing diversity projects
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]By embedding good practice on gender issues within our other programmes and partner organisations,
[normal] and given the right incentives and direction, we expect these to establish a wide reach and 
[normal]have a significant
[normal] impact on all areas of diversity and 
[normal]equality in the STEM workforce.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]BIS funds the 
[normal]Royal Society and Roy
[normal]al Academy of Engineering to lead
[normal] a programme of work
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]n partnership with the 
[normal]professional 
[normal]institutions, industry and others
[normal],
[normal] aimed at understanding and addressing issues of diversity in the STEM workforce.  
[normal]We want the STEM Diversity programme to achieve significant improvements in the 
[normal]diversity of the STEM workforce by identifying and r
[normal]emov
[normal]ing
[normal] barriers to joining STEM w
[normal]orkforce; i
[normal]mprov
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]retention and progression rates for people once they join the workforce. Importantly the STEM Diversity Programme is looking at issues affecting 
[normal]all m
[normal]inority or disadvantaged groups, not gender alone.  This also aligns with the wider government approach to equalities which move away from a more strand specific perspective.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Royal Society and the Royal Academy of Engineering are submitting evidence t
[normal]o this inquiry which will provide more detail of their activities under the STEM Diversity Programme.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Women's Business Council (WBC) was set up to look at ways of maximising women's contribution to economic growth and 
[normal]consider how best to
[normal] remov
[normal]e
[normal] the b
[normal]arriers that women face in playing a full part in business and the workplace.  Their report
[normal] included several recommendations on women in STEM.
[normal]  
[normal]The Government is currently drawing up an action plan for implementing the recommendations which will be published in the 
[normal]autumn
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]12.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]STEM
[normal] careers in both industry and academia require a specialist skill set.  More is being done to encourage both women and men into this sector via vocational routes such as apprenticeships, however the main route of entry, particularly into senior specialist 
[normal]roles or academic positions
[normal],
[normal] remains through the
[normal] 
[normal]HE route. 
[normal] 
[normal]Therefore in order to increase the number of women in science, it is important to address the issue of access and retention at HE level.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]13.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government is committed to access to HE based on talen
[normal]t and potential. 
[normal] 
[normal]In HE we have introduced a new framework for widening participation with increased responsibility placed on HEIs. 
[normal] 
[normal]This includes arrangements for annual access agreements.
[normal] 
[normal] HEIs agree their own access agreement measures and targets with t
[normal]he independent Director of Fair Access, in line with their own particular mission and challenges, and these can include targets on gender.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We have also asked the Office For Fair Access (OFFA) and the 
[normal]Higher Education 
[normal]Funding Council for England
[normal], in consultation with the HE sector, to develop a national strategy for access and student success. The overarching aim in developing the strategy is to ensure that everyone with the potential to benefit from higher education has an equal opportunity to p
[normal]articipate and succeed, regardless of background, age, ethnicity, disability or gender. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The interim report
[normal] on the development of the new strategy has highlighted the continuing disparity in entry rates between men and women in HE and showed how these mi
[normal]rror the differences between men and women in the A level population before HE entry.  Further consideration will be given to this 
[normal](
[normal]and other equality and diversity issues
[normal])
[normal] as the national strategy is developed through to autumn 2013. 
